Mister. listen!
This is my building.

42
00:01:51.198 --> 00:01:52.677
I can't just leave
them all to die.

43
00:01:52.721 --> 00:01:54.505
Listen. listen.
you need to calm down

44
00:01:54.549 --> 00:01:56.812
and let us do our job.
All right.
just stay to your right.

45
00:01:56.855 --> 00:01:59.206
stay to your right.
Let the firefighters through.

46
00:01:59.249 --> 00:02:00.772
Just one with me.
Top floor.

47
00:02:00.816 --> 00:02:02.774
I did everything I could.

48
00:02:02.818 --> 00:02:05.777
I really did. There was just
nothing more I could do.

49
00:02:05.821 --> 00:02:08.345
Well. let's examine
that statement. Mr. Wilson.

50
00:02:08.389 --> 00:02:11.218
You are the sole owner of the
apartment building. correct?

51
00:02:11.261 --> 00:02:13.785
Uh. yes. I-I've owned it
for years.

52
00:02:13.829 --> 00:02:16.397
And as such. you're responsible
for its upkeep.

53
00:02:16.440 --> 00:02:18.225
for its maintenance.

54
00:02:18.268 --> 00:02:20.792
Yes. That's correct.

55
00:02:20.836 --> 00:02:22.446
And because you're
responsible.

56
00:02:22.490 --> 00:02:24.622
you'd heard from
a city inspector

57
00:02:24.666 --> 00:02:26.755
that the boiler
in the basement was failing

58
00:02:26.798 --> 00:02:28.800
and needed to be replaced.
isn't that correct?

59
00:02:28.844 --> 00:02:31.194
That's true. but the cost...

60
00:02:31.238 --> 00:02:33.327
Yes or no. Mr. Wilson?

61
00:02:33.370 --> 00:02:35.198
Yes.

62
00:02:35.242 --> 00:02:37.157
Okay.

63
00:02:37.200 --> 00:02:40.203
But instead of replacing
the boiler. what did you do?

64
00:02:40.247 --> 00:02:42.901
I told my maintenance man
Nicholas to fix it.

65
00:02:42.945 --> 00:02:45.469
Nicholas Borrego. right?
What happened to him?

66
00:02:46.514 --> 00:02:49.604
He... he died.

67
00:02:49.647 --> 00:02:51.649
That's right. he died.

68
00:02:51.693 --> 00:02:53.695
And five other people died.

69
00:02:53.738 --> 00:02:56.611
They all went to sleep
and never woke up

70
00:02:56.654 --> 00:02:59.875
because the boiler
in the building failed.

71
00:02:59.918 --> 00:03:02.443
as you were warned would happen.

72
00:03:02.486 --> 00:03:06.186
They died because you were
trying to save a buck.

73
00:03:06.229 --> 00:03:08.710
Can he say that?
Is it gonna be like this?

74
00:03:08.753 --> 00:03:11.234
No. it's gonna be worse.

75
00:03:11.278 --> 00:03:14.194
The other side's gonna be
way harder on you than that.

76
00:03:15.543 --> 00:03:17.675
I'm not doing very well. am I?

77
00:03:17.719 --> 00:03:19.808
You'll get better.

78
00:03:19.851 --> 00:03:22.376
It feels to me. Ed.

79
00:03:22.419 --> 00:03:24.247
like you're holding back.

80
00:03:24.291 --> 00:03:27.337
But these people need
to understand how you feel.

81
00:03:27.381 --> 00:03:29.339
Six people died
in your building.

82
00:03:30.906 --> 00:03:33.343
How does that make you feel?

83
00:03:33.387 --> 00:03:35.432
It feels horrible.

84
00:03:35.476 --> 00:03:37.695
It's devastating.

85
00:03:37.739 --> 00:03:39.654
Okay. Keep going.

86
00:03:42.396 --> 00:03:44.528
I still can't believe
it happened.

87
00:03:44.572 --> 00:03:46.878
I knew those tenants.

88
00:03:46.922 --> 00:03:49.707
Some of them had been
in my building for years.

89
00:03:49.751 --> 00:03:51.318
You took care of them.

90
00:03:51.361 --> 00:03:55.365
I always took care
of the people in my building.

91
00:03:55.409 --> 00:03:57.367
Then why didn't you replace
the boiler

92
00:03:57.411 --> 00:03:59.326
when you learned it was failing?

93
00:03:59.369 --> 00:04:00.718
I wanted to.

94
00:04:00.762 --> 00:04:02.851
But with the pandemic

95
00:04:02.894 --> 00:04:06.420
and all the supply chain issues
a-and inflation.

96
00:04:06.463 --> 00:04:08.726
it was gonna cost
five times what it should've

97
00:04:08.770 --> 00:04:10.250
for me to replace it.

98
00:04:10.293 --> 00:04:12.252
I just didn't have
that kind of money.

99
00:04:12.295 --> 00:04:14.558
not after two years'
rent forbearance.

100
00:04:14.602 --> 00:04:16.734
Nicholas assured me

101
00:04:16.778 --> 00:04:18.040
he could fix it.

102
00:04:18.083 --> 00:04:20.434
least until I could build up
a cash reserve.

103
00:04:21.739 --> 00:04:23.393
And I believed him.

104
00:04:23.437 --> 00:04:26.918
I'd do anything to go
back and change things.

105
00:04:26.962 --> 00:04:28.964
But I can't.

106
00:04:30.661 --> 00:04:32.489
The truth is

107
00:04:32.533 --> 00:04:35.536
I was doing the best I could
with what I had.

108
00:04:38.452 --> 00:04:39.583
See?

109
00:04:39.627 --> 00:04:41.846
Better already.

110
00:04:41.890 --> 00:04:44.284
Oh. this is
Ed's insurance company calling.

111
00:04:44.327 --> 00:04:46.634
Keep going.
I'll be right back. Hey.

112
00:04:46.677 --> 00:04:50.638
Good timing.
Our star witness is doing great.

113
00:04:54.381 --> 00:04:56.861
Those look nice. Do they
come in an open toe?

114
00:04:56.905 --> 00:04:58.385
They keep your feet warm

115
00:04:58.428 --> 00:04:59.951
at 30 below zero. so I doubt it.

116
00:04:59.995 --> 00:05:02.998
Does it get 30 below
on Kilimanjaro?

117
00:05:03.041 --> 00:05:04.956
You got to be ready
for anything.

118
00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:06.349
I can't believe
you are traveling

119
00:05:06.393 --> 00:05:08.351
halfway across the world
with a guy you just met.

120
00:05:08.395 --> 00:05:10.962
That's so... spontaneous.

121
00:05:11.006 --> 00:05:13.356
I can't believe you're
climbing a freaking mountain.

122
00:05:13.400 --> 00:05:15.706
Guy put a gun to my head.
and you know what he gave me?

123
00:05:15.750 --> 00:05:17.578
A dhi.

124
00:05:19.362 --> 00:05:21.364
A barely passing grade?

125
00:05:21.408 --> 00:05:24.628
In Sanskrit.
it's insight or intellect.

126
00:05:24.672 --> 00:05:26.021
In Hindu philosophy.

127
00:05:26.064 --> 00:05:29.546
it's a gut instinct
you can't ignore.

128
00:05:31.548 --> 00:05:34.334
Going with Cameron.
climbing Kilimanjaro.

129
00:05:34.377 --> 00:05:36.031
that's my dhi.

130
00:05:37.032 --> 00:05:38.642
I wish I had a dhi.

131
00:05:38.686 --> 00:05:41.515
I think I might have one.

132
00:05:42.559 --> 00:05:44.474
Whoa. whoa. so that's it?
You're gonna settle

133
00:05:44.518 --> 00:05:46.607
without even hearing
our strategy?

134
00:05:46.650 --> 00:05:48.609
I know. the case has
challenges. and I...

135
00:05:48.652 --> 00:05:51.481
Please don't hang up. But...

136
00:05:51.525 --> 00:05:54.658
Gutless worm.

137
00:05:54.702 --> 00:05:56.617
Come in!

138
00:05:56.660 --> 00:05:58.401
Got a minute?

139
00:05:58.445 --> 00:06:00.360
Ed Wilson's insurance company
is settling

140
00:06:00.403 --> 00:06:02.753
the carbon monoxide suit.
We could've won that.

141
00:06:03.711 --> 00:06:05.843
Yes. maybe.

142
00:06:05.887 --> 00:06:08.542
Ever heard of a firm
called Ellis & Clifton?

143
00:06:08.585 --> 00:06:11.022
These insurance company guys.
I'll tell you.

144
00:06:11.066 --> 00:06:13.721
they are classic cowards.

145
00:06:13.764 --> 00:06:16.724
They're afraid of any kind
of fight. any conflict.

146
00:06:16.767 --> 00:06:18.595
You're right. they're the worst.
Answer my question.

147
00:06:18.639 --> 00:06:20.684
and I will put a hit out
on them for you.

148
00:06:20.728 --> 00:06:22.512
Ellis & Clifton?

149
00:06:22.556 --> 00:06:25.472
Chicago. Boutique firm. right?

150
00:06:25.515 --> 00:06:28.388
Bigger. 300 attorneys on staff.

151
00:06:28.431 --> 00:06:30.999
Wellman Hospitality
is one of their clients.

152
00:06:31.042 --> 00:06:32.522
Ooh. Wellman's is massive.

153
00:06:32.566 --> 00:06:34.698
Revenue's. what. six billion?

154
00:06:34.742 --> 00:06:37.048
8.3.
Hmm.

155
00:06:38.789 --> 00:06:40.095
What are you thinking?

156
00:06:40.138 --> 00:06:42.706
Ellis & Clifton
has been freelancing

157
00:06:42.750 --> 00:06:43.881
their trial analysis work.

158
00:06:43.925 --> 00:06:45.056
I want to pitch them

159
00:06:45.100 --> 00:06:48.582
on making TAC
their exclusive provider.

160
00:06:50.148 --> 00:06:52.673
It's ambitious. I mean.
we're stretched pretty thin.

161
00:06:52.716 --> 00:06:54.718
I don't know if we could
even service them right now.

162
00:06:54.762 --> 00:06:56.198
We can if we reinvest

163
00:06:56.241 --> 00:06:58.418
the money from Smokestack Labs.
take on more staff.

164
00:06:58.461 --> 00:06:59.984
more office space.

165
00:07:00.028 --> 00:07:03.423
What makes you think
Ellis & Clifton would say yes?

166
00:07:03.466 --> 00:07:04.728
'Cause we're gonna show them

167
00:07:04.772 --> 00:07:07.557
how we can seriously improve
their win rate.

168
00:07:07.601 --> 00:07:10.995
Because you already have
the numbers that prove we can.

169
00:07:11.039 --> 00:07:13.868
Would I be sitting here
if I didn't?

170
00:07:14.912 --> 00:07:16.436
I like this idea.

171
00:07:16.479 --> 00:07:18.438
All right.
How do we get started?

172
00:07:18.481 --> 00:07:20.048
We have a problem.

173
00:07:20.091 --> 00:07:21.571
Look. I think we're being

174
00:07:21.615 --> 00:07:22.746
a bit premature here.

175
00:07:22.790 --> 00:07:23.921
Why don't we go talk
in the office.

176
00:07:23.965 --> 00:07:25.619
I'm sorry. Chester.
This is happening.

177
00:07:25.662 --> 00:07:26.881
What's going on?

178
00:07:26.924 --> 00:07:28.839
Uh. Dr. Bull. this
is Detective Orwell.

179
00:07:28.883 --> 00:07:31.451
He's here to execute
an arrest warrant on Mr. Wilson.

180
00:07:31.494 --> 00:07:32.669
What's the charge?

181
00:07:32.713 --> 00:07:33.888
Negligent homicide.
six counts.

182
00:07:33.931 --> 00:07:36.020
I don't understand. Homicide?

183
00:07:36.064 --> 00:07:37.457
They can't...
You have
the right to remain silent.

184
00:07:37.500 --> 00:07:38.806
They can't do this. can they?
Anything you say

185
00:07:38.849 --> 00:07:39.937
can and will be used against you
in a court of law.

186
00:07:39.981 --> 00:07:40.982
At least let him self-surrender.

187
00:07:41.025 --> 00:07:42.113
I will guarantee his appearance.

188
00:07:42.157 --> 00:07:43.506
- You have my word.
- I'm sorry.

189
00:07:43.550 --> 00:07:45.508
I can't do that when the charges
are this serious.

190
00:07:45.552 --> 00:07:47.945
These charges are outrageous.
and you know it.
What I know

191
00:07:47.989 --> 00:07:49.991
- is that six people are dead.
- You don't

192
00:07:50.034 --> 00:07:52.210
show up personally
to arrest everyone you charge.

193
00:07:52.254 --> 00:07:54.865
If you have a bone to pick
with me. this...
Oh. this isn't about you.

194
00:07:55.910 --> 00:07:56.954
Either of you.

195
00:08:00.001 --> 00:08:02.569
The guard at the front desk
just texted.

196
00:08:02.612 --> 00:08:04.527
Apparently there are press
in the lobby downstairs.

197
00:08:04.571 --> 00:08:06.703
Oh. son of a bitch.

198
00:08:09.053 --> 00:08:10.620
Now I get it.

199
00:08:10.664 --> 00:08:13.144
This is all about
the perp walk. right?

200
00:08:13.188 --> 00:08:15.625
You're gonna parade Ed
in front of the cameras

201
00:08:15.669 --> 00:08:18.149
until you get a nice interview
on the news tonight?

202
00:08:18.193 --> 00:08:19.629
If the press is interested.

203
00:08:19.673 --> 00:08:21.501
I will talk to them
all day long.

204
00:08:21.544 --> 00:08:22.763
It's what you would do.

205
00:08:22.806 --> 00:08:24.808
Where are they taking me?

206
00:08:24.852 --> 00:08:27.594
Don't worry. Ed. I'll be down to
handle your arraignment. okay?

207
00:08:27.637 --> 00:08:29.639
Don't talk to anyone about
anything until Mr. Palmer

208
00:08:29.683 --> 00:08:31.075
gets there.
And don't worry.

209
00:08:31.119 --> 00:08:32.903
We've beaten this showboat

210
00:08:32.947 --> 00:08:35.253
in court before. Twice.

211
00:08:35.297 --> 00:08:37.865
Oh. Well.
third time's the charm.

212
00:08:40.998 --> 00:08:42.913
It's a good thing you're
not still dating that guy.

213
00:08:42.957 --> 00:08:45.525
'cause I'm gonna
pulverize him.

214
00:08:45.568 --> 00:08:47.527
♪

215
00:08:54.577 --> 00:08:55.709
Okay. did you see
the Ledger today?

216
00:08:55.752 --> 00:08:58.538
"Justice for Sale."

217
00:08:58.581 --> 00:08:59.713
They're talking about us.

218
00:08:59.756 --> 00:09:01.279
- I saw.
- "Landlord

219
00:09:01.323 --> 00:09:02.585
"Ed Wilson has retained

220
00:09:02.629 --> 00:09:04.718
"the high-priced
Trial Analysis Corporation.

221
00:09:04.761 --> 00:09:07.547
which has been mired
in controversy since..."

222
00:09:07.590 --> 00:09:08.765
"Mired"?

223
00:09:08.809 --> 00:09:10.419
I was arrested once.

224
00:09:10.462 --> 00:09:12.203
Scandal sells papers.

225
00:09:12.247 --> 00:09:14.336
You know who's behind this.
don't you?

226
00:09:14.379 --> 00:09:16.468
The A.D.A.Rob!

227
00:09:16.512 --> 00:09:18.209
He's trying to
bias the jury pool

228
00:09:18.253 --> 00:09:20.211
and paint us as mercenaries.

229
00:09:20.255 --> 00:09:22.736
You have to ignore the noise.

230
00:09:22.779 --> 00:09:24.607
But it's just so noisy.

231
00:09:24.651 --> 00:09:26.783
Are we sticking
with the same strategy

232
00:09:26.827 --> 00:09:28.219
as the civil suit?

233
00:09:28.263 --> 00:09:29.569
Yes. Ed is a good man

234
00:09:29.612 --> 00:09:31.701
caught in a perfect storm
of bad circumstances.

235
00:09:31.745 --> 00:09:36.010
Punishing him would
only pile tragedy upon tragedy.
Right.

236
00:09:37.272 --> 00:09:39.230
You and I
need to start talking voir dire.

237
00:09:39.274 --> 00:09:40.623
It's set for Tuesday.

238
00:09:40.667 --> 00:09:42.233
No. I... That is the same day

239
00:09:42.277 --> 00:09:43.626
that we're having lunch
with Aurora Clifton.

240
00:09:43.670 --> 00:09:46.586
Who?
Aurora Clifton of Ellis & Clifton.

241
00:09:46.629 --> 00:09:48.631
the massive firm
that we're pitching.

242
00:09:48.675 --> 00:09:49.980
Oh. yeah.

243
00:09:50.024 --> 00:09:52.417
Sorry. That was
before Ed got dragged out

244
00:09:52.461 --> 00:09:54.637
of here in cuffs.
Let's reschedule.

245
00:09:54.681 --> 00:09:56.900
I begged for this meeting. Bull.

246
00:09:56.944 --> 00:09:59.773
Aurora is in town now
for a wrongful death trial.

247
00:09:59.816 --> 00:10:02.689
She made clear
her schedule is very tight.

248
00:10:02.732 --> 00:10:04.386
Oh.

249
00:10:04.429 --> 00:10:07.258
Well. fine. You do lunch.

250
00:10:07.302 --> 00:10:08.869
Without you?
Sure.

251
00:10:08.912 --> 00:10:10.784
We're partners.

252
00:10:10.827 --> 00:10:13.830
We've got to learn
to divide and conquer sometime.

253
00:10:13.874 --> 00:10:16.267
especially
if we're planning to expand.

254
00:10:16.311 --> 00:10:19.053
No argument here.

255
00:10:21.795 --> 00:10:23.448
Dr. Bull. Mr. Palmer.

256
00:10:23.492 --> 00:10:24.928
Oh.

257
00:10:24.972 --> 00:10:26.451
Hey. Ed. How
you holding up?

258
00:10:26.495 --> 00:10:28.540
Good. Good.

259
00:10:29.585 --> 00:10:30.934
Well. terrible. actually.

260
00:10:30.978 --> 00:10:32.632
I haven't been sleeping.

261
00:10:32.675 --> 00:10:34.982
Well. that's only natural. Ed.

262
00:10:35.025 --> 00:10:38.289
I spent all last night
researching jury selection.

263
00:10:38.333 --> 00:10:39.813
and I've got some ideas.

264
00:10:39.856 --> 00:10:40.944
Okay. Um.

265
00:10:40.988 --> 00:10:42.685
well. thank you.

266
00:10:42.729 --> 00:10:44.905
but we've got
voir dire covered. Ed.

267
00:10:44.948 --> 00:10:48.648
I know you're the experts.
and I know this is annoying.

268
00:10:48.691 --> 00:10:50.693
but when I'm anxious.

269
00:10:50.737 --> 00:10:53.783
it helps me to focus
on solving a problem.

270
00:10:53.827 --> 00:10:56.351
Well. fire away. The
more brains the better.

271
00:10:56.394 --> 00:10:59.049
I think it's really important
that we kick all the renters

272
00:10:59.093 --> 00:11:00.572
off my jury

273
00:11:00.616 --> 00:11:02.400
because they're predisposed
to dislike landlords.

274
00:11:02.444 --> 00:11:04.228
That's a good idea.
but in this city.

275
00:11:04.272 --> 00:11:05.708
70% of the people rent.

276
00:11:05.752 --> 00:11:07.797
so we can't get rid
of all of them.

277
00:11:07.841 --> 00:11:09.930
We're gonna be weeding
out people who are inclined

278
00:11:09.973 --> 00:11:11.714
to blame you for this tragedy.

279
00:11:11.758 --> 00:11:14.586
People who have
what we call a Bad Actor Bias.

280
00:11:14.630 --> 00:11:16.676
What's that?
Well. it is
the belief that when

281
00:11:16.719 --> 00:11:18.678
terrible things happen.
someone has to be to blame.

282
00:11:18.721 --> 00:11:20.680
and that allows people to ignore

283
00:11:20.723 --> 00:11:23.465
the fact that
accidents can happen

284
00:11:23.508 --> 00:11:25.380
and ruin our lives
at any moment.

285
00:11:25.423 --> 00:11:26.729
So. how do we spot these people?

286
00:11:26.773 --> 00:11:28.252
It's easy.

287
00:11:28.296 --> 00:11:31.952
Mr. Palmer is gonna ask
them questions about blame.

288
00:11:31.995 --> 00:11:34.128
Ladies and gentlemen.
today I want to speak with you

289
00:11:34.171 --> 00:11:35.520
about blame.

290
00:11:35.564 --> 00:11:36.957
- Oh. no.
- About a week ago in Boston...

291
00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:39.089
Not good.
Not good at all.

292
00:11:39.133 --> 00:11:41.004
What's not good?
What's happening?

293
00:11:41.048 --> 00:11:43.224
The prosecutor is
using our strategy.

294
00:11:43.267 --> 00:11:46.140
Except he wants to keep jurors
with Bad Actor Bias.

295
00:11:46.183 --> 00:11:48.272
- and we want to eliminate them.
- Juror number eight.

296
00:11:48.316 --> 00:11:50.318
Why do you think the car
swerved off the road?

297
00:11:50.361 --> 00:11:52.276
I bet the roads were slick.

298
00:11:52.320 --> 00:11:54.278
We've had a lot of rain.
Ah.

299
00:11:54.322 --> 00:11:57.020
Your Honor. the People would
like to thank and excuse

300
00:11:57.064 --> 00:11:58.674
juror number eight.
If we stick with our strategy.

301
00:11:58.718 --> 00:12:00.154
it's gonna be a
war of attrition

302
00:12:00.197 --> 00:12:01.677
until both sides
are out of strikes.

303
00:12:01.721 --> 00:12:04.158
Then we're just left
with who we get.

304
00:12:04.201 --> 00:12:05.376
We need to call an audible.

305
00:12:05.420 --> 00:12:06.900
What do you mean?

306
00:12:06.943 --> 00:12:08.684
Well. Rob's picks
are gonna blame you

307
00:12:08.728 --> 00:12:10.338
for the carbon monoxide
poisoning.

308
00:12:10.381 --> 00:12:13.167
but that doesn't mean they
can't find a little forgiveness.

309
00:12:13.210 --> 00:12:14.429
We're looking
for compassion.

310
00:12:14.472 --> 00:12:16.736
Okay. but I'm gonna need
some new questions.

311
00:12:16.779 --> 00:12:18.172
Like. now.

312
00:12:18.215 --> 00:12:20.000
Yeah. There aren't
any good questions.

313
00:12:20.043 --> 00:12:21.653
You ask somebody
if they're compassionate.

314
00:12:21.697 --> 00:12:23.090
they're only gonna lie.

315
00:12:23.133 --> 00:12:24.700
To make themselves look good.

316
00:12:24.744 --> 00:12:27.747
But we have
a secret weapon. Taylor?

317
00:12:27.790 --> 00:12:28.835
Scouring for compassion

318
00:12:28.878 --> 00:12:30.880
as we speak.

319
00:12:30.924 --> 00:12:32.795
Um. juror 11

320
00:12:32.839 --> 00:12:35.755
has Facebook posts
about donating to charity.

321
00:12:35.798 --> 00:12:38.192
Well. let's ignore that.
We don't know if she did it

322
00:12:38.235 --> 00:12:40.629
out of the goodness of her heart
or for the likes.

323
00:12:40.672 --> 00:12:42.544
Then what am I looking for?

324
00:12:42.587 --> 00:12:44.894
People who have survived things.

325
00:12:44.938 --> 00:12:47.767
things that others judge.

326
00:12:47.810 --> 00:12:50.291
Something that fosters empathy.

327
00:12:50.334 --> 00:12:52.293
Maybe someone
who's been fired for misconduct

328
00:12:52.336 --> 00:12:55.687
or an alcoholic
who's gotten sober.

329
00:12:55.731 --> 00:12:57.037
Got it.

330
00:12:57.080 --> 00:12:59.691
Juror number 15.

331
00:12:59.735 --> 00:13:01.128
what do you think was
the cause of this fire?

332
00:13:01.171 --> 00:13:03.173
Someone probably left
a cigarette burning.

333
00:13:03.217 --> 00:13:05.654
Or maybe a candle.

334
00:13:05.697 --> 00:13:07.874
People can be so reckless.

335
00:13:07.917 --> 00:13:11.181
Your Honor. this juror is
acceptable to the prosecution.

336
00:13:11.225 --> 00:13:13.705
Of course she is.
Taylor. any reason

337
00:13:13.749 --> 00:13:15.272
we don't kick this woman
to the curb?

338
00:13:16.708 --> 00:13:19.059
Actually.
she went bankrupt. Yay!

339
00:13:19.102 --> 00:13:20.800
Now I feel like an ass.

340
00:13:20.843 --> 00:13:21.931
Mr. Palmer?

341
00:13:23.063 --> 00:13:26.588
Uh. the defense has no objection
to this juror. Your Honor.

342
00:13:26.631 --> 00:13:28.242
Dr. Bull is sorry
he isn't able to be here.

343
00:13:28.285 --> 00:13:31.027
One of our cases
just became a five-alarm fire.

344
00:13:31.071 --> 00:13:32.899
and our clients
always come first.

345
00:13:32.942 --> 00:13:34.726
I'm sure you understand.

346
00:13:34.770 --> 00:13:36.076
I'm in the middle of trial.

347
00:13:36.119 --> 00:13:39.079
I don't have time
to have this conversation twice.

348
00:13:39.122 --> 00:13:41.908
Let's reschedule down the road
when all parties can join.

349
00:13:41.951 --> 00:13:43.997
2002.

350
00:13:44.040 --> 00:13:46.347
You worked for Cooper
Ellis & Associates

351
00:13:46.390 --> 00:13:47.914
as a senior associate.

352
00:13:47.957 --> 00:13:50.830
Then along came the biggest
copyright case in a decade.

353
00:13:50.873 --> 00:13:54.137
and Mr. Ellis asked you
to second chair.

354
00:13:54.181 --> 00:13:56.748
Ms. Morgan. while I admire that
you've done your research...

355
00:13:56.792 --> 00:13:58.272
Except halfway through trial.

356
00:13:58.315 --> 00:14:00.056
your boss
suffered a heart attack.

357
00:14:00.100 --> 00:14:01.928
I'm guessing at that point.

358
00:14:01.971 --> 00:14:03.190
the client wanted a mistrial.

359
00:14:03.233 --> 00:14:04.931
and the judge
surely would've granted it.

360
00:14:04.974 --> 00:14:07.281
But somehow
you convinced the client

361
00:14:07.324 --> 00:14:09.109
that you didn't need Mr. Ellis

362
00:14:09.152 --> 00:14:11.633
and went on
to win that case alone.

363
00:14:11.676 --> 00:14:12.939
One year later.

364
00:14:12.982 --> 00:14:16.159
the firm was renamed
Ellis & Clifton.

365
00:14:16.203 --> 00:14:17.900
Your point?

366
00:14:17.944 --> 00:14:20.642
If both partners
are the best of the best.

367
00:14:20.685 --> 00:14:23.863
sometimes you only need one
to get it done.

368
00:14:27.736 --> 00:14:29.216
Shall we order some apps?

369
00:14:29.259 --> 00:14:31.653
Miss?

370
00:14:31.696 --> 00:14:35.091
Okay. Taylor. what do we know
about these last two candidates?

371
00:14:35.135 --> 00:14:38.094
Uh. hold on a second. Bull.

372
00:14:38.138 --> 00:14:39.879
Mauricio's school is calling.

373
00:14:39.922 --> 00:14:42.229
Hello. This is Taylor Rentzel.

374
00:14:42.272 --> 00:14:44.971
Oh. my God. What happened?

375
00:14:45.014 --> 00:14:46.320
Of course. I'm on my way.

376
00:14:46.363 --> 00:14:48.148
Bull. I have to go.

377
00:14:48.191 --> 00:14:50.715
Right now? We only have
one juror left to seat.

378
00:14:50.759 --> 00:14:52.065
Mauricio got hurt.
He's on his way

379
00:14:52.108 --> 00:14:53.936
to the emergency room.
I have to go. I'm sorry.

380
00:14:53.980 --> 00:14:55.155
Taylor's gone.

381
00:14:55.198 --> 00:14:57.418
Mr. Palmer. it's your turn.

382
00:14:57.461 --> 00:14:58.854
Uh...

383
00:15:00.987 --> 00:15:02.989
I need a question
that gets us to compassion.

384
00:15:03.032 --> 00:15:04.251
There aren't any good questions.

385
00:15:04.294 --> 00:15:05.948
- Come on. Bull.
- Mr. Palmer.

386
00:15:05.992 --> 00:15:07.994
- I'd like to wrap this up today.
- Uh.

387
00:15:08.037 --> 00:15:10.866
y-yes. Your Honor.
Just one moment. please.

388
00:15:10.910 --> 00:15:12.694
Come on.
there's got to be something.

389
00:15:12.737 --> 00:15:14.348
I mean...There is.

390
00:15:14.391 --> 00:15:16.132
But you're not gonna like it.

391
00:15:16.176 --> 00:15:17.133
What?

392
00:15:17.177 --> 00:15:18.178
Sorry.

393
00:15:18.221 --> 00:15:20.136
What? Ow. Hey!

394
00:15:21.137 --> 00:15:22.922
Bull!

395
00:15:22.965 --> 00:15:24.445
Check juror 26.
What?

396
00:15:24.488 --> 00:15:26.099
Juror 26. He feels

397
00:15:26.142 --> 00:15:27.404
real bad for you.

398
00:15:29.493 --> 00:15:31.452
Your Honor. uh.

399
00:15:31.495 --> 00:15:35.282
juror 26 is acceptable
to the defense.

400
00:15:35.325 --> 00:15:36.936
Well-played in there.

401
00:15:36.979 --> 00:15:38.938
I mean. mostly for Bull.
And your client.

402
00:15:38.981 --> 00:15:41.070
You may have gotten the
soggy end of that stick.
You think?

403
00:15:41.114 --> 00:15:43.594
Listen. you got a decent jury.
That's all that matters.

404
00:15:43.638 --> 00:15:44.987
This might stain.

405
00:15:45.031 --> 00:15:46.554
I never liked
that shirt anyway.

406
00:15:46.597 --> 00:15:48.686
You said
you loved this shirt.

407
00:15:48.730 --> 00:15:50.036
Oh. I was lying.

408
00:15:50.079 --> 00:15:51.994
This may actually be
an improvement.

409
00:15:53.039 --> 00:15:54.214
Shut up.

410
00:15:55.258 --> 00:15:56.956
With every case

411
00:15:56.999 --> 00:15:59.523
we try. every mirror
jury we analyze.

412
00:15:59.567 --> 00:16:01.395
we continue to refine

413
00:16:01.438 --> 00:16:02.918
our algorithm.
You and your clients

414
00:16:02.962 --> 00:16:05.312
will get the benefit
of the 13 years

415
00:16:05.355 --> 00:16:09.403
that we have spent perfecting
our predictive behavior models.

416
00:16:09.446 --> 00:16:11.405
I'm impressed
by TAC's track record.

417
00:16:11.448 --> 00:16:13.015
You're clearly doing
something right.

418
00:16:13.059 --> 00:16:14.712
My next meeting is here.

419
00:16:14.756 --> 00:16:16.671
You've given me a lot
to think about. Marissa.

420
00:16:16.714 --> 00:16:17.977
I'll be in touch.

421
00:16:18.020 --> 00:16:20.631
Thank you.
Looking forward to it.

422
00:16:20.675 --> 00:16:22.807
Bradley.Marissa.

423
00:16:23.852 --> 00:16:25.767
Aurora. it's so nice
to meet you in person.

424
00:16:25.810 --> 00:16:27.464
How do you two...?

425
00:16:27.508 --> 00:16:28.248
I called Bradley

426
00:16:28.291 --> 00:16:29.031
to do my due diligence.

427
00:16:29.075 --> 00:16:30.685
After he raved about you.

428
00:16:30.728 --> 00:16:32.556
he mentioned
that he recently launched

429
00:16:32.600 --> 00:16:34.645
his own trial science division.

430
00:16:35.690 --> 00:16:37.213
Really? Since when?

431
00:16:37.257 --> 00:16:39.041
Well. I got my algorithm
up and running

432
00:16:39.085 --> 00:16:40.738
shortly after you
left the firm.

433
00:16:40.782 --> 00:16:42.740
Actually. well.

434
00:16:42.784 --> 00:16:45.047
it would be fair to say
that you inspired me.

435
00:16:46.092 --> 00:16:47.919
I bet I did.

436
00:16:47.963 --> 00:16:50.226
Well. I decided I might as well
hear from both of you

437
00:16:50.270 --> 00:16:51.706
while I'm in town.

438
00:16:51.749 --> 00:16:55.014
Of course. Super. Well...

439
00:16:55.057 --> 00:16:57.320
May the best firm win.

440
00:17:07.287 --> 00:17:09.767
Mauricio had to get
eight stitches.

441
00:17:09.811 --> 00:17:11.726
It was awful.
He was so upset.

442
00:17:11.769 --> 00:17:13.075
I thought I'd never
get him to calm down.

443
00:17:13.119 --> 00:17:15.338
What happened?

444
00:17:15.382 --> 00:17:17.601
Some kid pushed him
off the monkey bars.

445
00:17:17.645 --> 00:17:20.126
Oh. my God.
What a little monster.

446
00:17:20.169 --> 00:17:21.649
Yeah. I don't know. maybe.

447
00:17:21.692 --> 00:17:24.304
I mean. turns out
Mauricio started the fight.

448
00:17:24.347 --> 00:17:25.870
Oh.

449
00:17:25.914 --> 00:17:27.089
I know.

450
00:17:27.133 --> 00:17:29.352
He's been acting out a bit
since Erik left.

451
00:17:29.396 --> 00:17:31.093
That's a big transition.

452
00:17:31.137 --> 00:17:33.269
I'm sure
he'll settle down in time.

453
00:17:34.314 --> 00:17:35.750
Hope you're right.

454
00:17:35.793 --> 00:17:37.273
I have a conference later
with his teacher

455
00:17:37.317 --> 00:17:39.101
to discuss "the incident."

456
00:17:39.145 --> 00:17:40.407
Can't wait.

457
00:17:41.669 --> 00:17:42.757
So...Mm.

458
00:17:42.800 --> 00:17:44.237
How do you think
Bradley Lena

459
00:17:44.280 --> 00:17:46.152
got his own jury algorithm
up and running so quickly?

460
00:17:46.195 --> 00:17:47.979
Simple. He looked
under the hood of mine

461
00:17:48.023 --> 00:17:49.416
while we were
working together.

462
00:17:49.459 --> 00:17:53.289
Hired engineers to scrape
together a cheap imitation.

463
00:17:53.333 --> 00:17:54.769
So he stole it from you?

464
00:17:54.812 --> 00:17:56.640
Well. legally. no.

465
00:17:56.684 --> 00:17:59.034
In reality. yes.

466
00:17:59.078 --> 00:18:01.906
Okay. he has an algorithm.

467
00:18:01.950 --> 00:18:03.821
But does he know
how to interpret the results?

468
00:18:03.865 --> 00:18:06.041
I mean. you've been doing this
for years.

469
00:18:06.085 --> 00:18:08.217
He's just getting started.

470
00:18:08.261 --> 00:18:10.654
What Bradley lacks
in experience and morals

471
00:18:10.698 --> 00:18:12.830
he more than makes up for
in salesmanship.

472
00:18:12.874 --> 00:18:16.007
He will have Aurora eating
out of the palm of his hand.

473
00:18:16.051 --> 00:18:18.314
So. he's a smooth talker.

474
00:18:18.358 --> 00:18:21.404
But you know what they say.
Actions speak louder than words.

475
00:18:22.927 --> 00:18:25.147
You're right. Great idea.

476
00:18:27.149 --> 00:18:29.108
What idea?

477
00:18:29.151 --> 00:18:31.806
The beeping sound woke me up.

478
00:18:31.849 --> 00:18:33.112
I felt

479
00:18:33.155 --> 00:18:34.591
so sick.

480
00:18:34.635 --> 00:18:36.332
I knew
something was really wrong.

481
00:18:36.376 --> 00:18:39.074
I wanted to get Julie. my wife.
out of the building.

482
00:18:39.118 --> 00:18:42.382
but before I could...

483
00:18:44.775 --> 00:18:46.777
...I passed out.

484
00:18:49.780 --> 00:18:52.000
I couldn't save her.

485
00:18:52.043 --> 00:18:55.264
Josh. your wife's death
is not your fault.

486
00:18:55.308 --> 00:18:57.353
Okay. I know this must be
incredibly difficult for you.

487
00:18:57.397 --> 00:18:58.833
If you want to take a second.

488
00:18:58.876 --> 00:19:00.704
just...I'm fine.

489
00:19:03.664 --> 00:19:05.753
Do you know the name
Nicholas Borrego?

490
00:19:06.797 --> 00:19:10.366
Sure. He was the maintenance man
for our apartment building.

491
00:19:10.410 --> 00:19:12.238
The maintenance man
that the defendant used

492
00:19:12.281 --> 00:19:13.891
to repair the boiler.

493
00:19:13.935 --> 00:19:17.068
Did you have any memorable
interactions with Mr. Borrego?

494
00:19:17.112 --> 00:19:19.114
Two months
before the carbon monoxide leak.

495
00:19:19.158 --> 00:19:21.116
he came to fix
the garbage disposal.

496
00:19:21.160 --> 00:19:23.945
I smelled alcohol on his breath.

497
00:19:23.988 --> 00:19:26.252
- He was drunk?
- Yeah.

498
00:19:26.295 --> 00:19:28.471
He was slurring his words.
and he dropped his tools

499
00:19:28.515 --> 00:19:29.777
a few times.

500
00:19:29.820 --> 00:19:31.996
Uh. can you think of any reason

501
00:19:32.040 --> 00:19:34.216
why the defendant
would have fired

502
00:19:34.260 --> 00:19:35.870
his previous maintenance company

503
00:19:35.913 --> 00:19:37.828
even though they had
an impeccable service record

504
00:19:37.872 --> 00:19:39.743
and-and replaced them
with this man

505
00:19:39.787 --> 00:19:41.354
- who drank on the job?
- Objection.

506
00:19:41.397 --> 00:19:43.094
This witness cannot testify

507
00:19:43.138 --> 00:19:45.488
to my client's state of mind
or decision-making.

508
00:19:45.532 --> 00:19:47.360
- Your Honor.
- Your Honor. the witness has

509
00:19:47.403 --> 00:19:50.754
direct knowledge of the subject
from the deceased.

510
00:19:50.798 --> 00:19:51.973
Overruled.

511
00:19:52.016 --> 00:19:53.366
The witness
may answer the question.

512
00:19:54.454 --> 00:19:57.805
Nicholas said
that he and Ed were old friends

513
00:19:57.848 --> 00:20:00.764
- and that Ed owed him one.
- No.

514
00:20:00.808 --> 00:20:02.288
That's wrong.
Not here. Ed.

515
00:20:02.331 --> 00:20:05.813
But it wasn't how he's making it seem.
I said not here.

516
00:20:05.856 --> 00:20:07.989
And now your wife

517
00:20:08.032 --> 00:20:10.470
and five other people are dead?

518
00:20:11.514 --> 00:20:14.474
No further questions.
Your Honor.

519
00:20:17.172 --> 00:20:18.913
Why didn't you
tell me you had a history

520
00:20:18.956 --> 00:20:19.957
with your maintenance guy?

521
00:20:20.001 --> 00:20:21.176
I hired Nicholas

522
00:20:21.220 --> 00:20:22.438
because he'd worked
for me before

523
00:20:22.482 --> 00:20:23.787
when I was a contractor.

524
00:20:23.831 --> 00:20:25.311
Yeah. I owed him a solid.

525
00:20:25.354 --> 00:20:27.138
but we weren't friends.

526
00:20:27.182 --> 00:20:28.966
He was qualified and licensed.

527
00:20:29.010 --> 00:20:30.968
No. he was drinking
on the job.

528
00:20:31.012 --> 00:20:32.970
That man's wife called
with problems

529
00:20:33.014 --> 00:20:34.145
at all hours of the night.

530
00:20:34.189 --> 00:20:36.452
Wasn't he ever allowed
to have a few beers?

531
00:20:36.496 --> 00:20:38.149
This...

532
00:20:38.193 --> 00:20:39.934
This is really bad.
isn't it?

533
00:20:41.196 --> 00:20:42.371
It certainly didn't help.

534
00:20:42.415 --> 00:20:44.199
We're gonna lose.

535
00:20:44.243 --> 00:20:46.854
I'm gonna go to prison.
Hey. Ed.

536
00:20:46.897 --> 00:20:48.856
We're not there yet.

537
00:20:48.899 --> 00:20:50.292
We're gonna get
an HVAC expert

538
00:20:50.336 --> 00:20:52.990
to testify how qualified
Nick was to do his job.

539
00:20:53.034 --> 00:20:55.558
and we're gonna get
experts to back him up.

540
00:20:55.602 --> 00:20:57.212
In fact. we're gonna
parade so many experts

541
00:20:57.256 --> 00:20:59.867
through that courtroom.
the jury is gonna be sick

542
00:20:59.910 --> 00:21:02.261
of hearing how
qualified Nicholas was.

543
00:21:03.958 --> 00:21:05.089
Okay.

544
00:21:06.090 --> 00:21:07.353
Okay.

545
00:21:08.484 --> 00:21:10.094
I know that what
Mauricio did was wrong.

546
00:21:10.138 --> 00:21:13.010
and believe me. I've had a
long talk with him about it.

547
00:21:13.054 --> 00:21:16.057
But he's been having a
really hard time lately.

548
00:21:16.100 --> 00:21:18.494
My ex-husband recently
moved to Hawaii...

549
00:21:18.538 --> 00:21:20.366
Ms. Rentzel....and he and Mauricio
are really close.

550
00:21:20.409 --> 00:21:21.932
And they speak on
Zoom every night.

551
00:21:21.976 --> 00:21:24.239
but it's not the same
as having him here.

552
00:21:24.283 --> 00:21:27.024
Ms. Rentzel. I do not believe
what's going on with Mauricio

553
00:21:27.068 --> 00:21:29.462
is because his father
moved away.

554
00:21:29.505 --> 00:21:31.507
You don't?
No.

555
00:21:31.551 --> 00:21:35.250
Although I think it's possible
that his absence

556
00:21:35.294 --> 00:21:39.080
is revealing
some other preexisting issues.

557
00:21:40.647 --> 00:21:43.040
Issues? What-what issues?

558
00:21:43.084 --> 00:21:45.347
Lack of focus.
trouble finishing tasks.

559
00:21:45.391 --> 00:21:47.044
waiting his turn.

560
00:21:47.088 --> 00:21:49.525
He's a little kid.
That's only natural.

561
00:21:49.569 --> 00:21:51.571
I spend all day
with little kids.

562
00:21:51.614 --> 00:21:56.053
What I'm talking about
is outside normal.

563
00:21:57.533 --> 00:21:59.274
What does that mean?

564
00:22:00.275 --> 00:22:04.061
I think Mauricio may have ADHD.

565
00:22:05.062 --> 00:22:07.195
No. He just has a lot of energy.

566
00:22:07.238 --> 00:22:10.241
I know some people feel
there's a stigma to ADHD.

567
00:22:10.285 --> 00:22:11.895
but there's nothing...It's not about a stigma.

568
00:22:11.939 --> 00:22:14.202
It's... I just don't think...

569
00:22:14.245 --> 00:22:16.291
I mean. you're not a doctor.

570
00:22:16.335 --> 00:22:17.901
I know.

571
00:22:17.945 --> 00:22:19.250
I'm telling you this

572
00:22:19.294 --> 00:22:21.644
so you can have your son
evaluated by one.

573
00:22:21.688 --> 00:22:25.692
This isn't something you want
to ignore. Ms. Rentzel.

574
00:22:28.172 --> 00:22:29.565
In these situations.

575
00:22:29.609 --> 00:22:31.915
live feedback
from our parallel jurors

576
00:22:31.959 --> 00:22:34.135
will offer insights
that you and your clients

577
00:22:34.178 --> 00:22:36.093
can use to adjust
defense strategy on the fly.

578
00:22:36.137 --> 00:22:38.618
Hi. I'm so sorry
for the interruption.

579
00:22:38.661 --> 00:22:41.316
Oh. Marissa. I'm not scheduled
to hear from you until tomorrow.

580
00:22:41.360 --> 00:22:42.926
Unfortunately.
what I have to say can't wait.

581
00:22:42.970 --> 00:22:44.493
I'm sure Bradley
will understand.

582
00:22:44.537 --> 00:22:46.408
We'll just be a few more minutes. Marissa.
It's about

583
00:22:46.452 --> 00:22:48.149
your wrongful death trial.

584
00:22:48.192 --> 00:22:49.237
- What about it?
- I know

585
00:22:49.280 --> 00:22:50.281
that you're expecting

586
00:22:50.325 --> 00:22:51.457
a verdict soon.

587
00:22:51.500 --> 00:22:52.936
The jury is deliberating now.

588
00:22:52.980 --> 00:22:54.024
I also know the other side

589
00:22:54.068 --> 00:22:56.070
has a settlement offer
on the table

590
00:22:56.113 --> 00:22:57.245
for $20 million.

591
00:22:57.288 --> 00:23:00.422
I am here to tell you
to take that deal.

592
00:23:00.466 --> 00:23:01.945
- Why would I do that?
- Because I

593
00:23:01.989 --> 00:23:04.905
spent all night
running mock trials of the case.

594
00:23:04.948 --> 00:23:06.341
What kind of stunt is this?

595
00:23:06.385 --> 00:23:08.691
And the upshot is
you are going to lose.

596
00:23:08.735 --> 00:23:10.954
We feel very good
about this jury.
I'm sorry.

597
00:23:10.998 --> 00:23:13.304
but you're going to lose.
and the jury

598
00:23:13.348 --> 00:23:15.524
is going to award
much higher damages

599
00:23:15.568 --> 00:23:17.439
than even
your worst-case scenario.

600
00:23:17.483 --> 00:23:19.963
$45 million to $50 million.

601
00:23:20.007 --> 00:23:22.444
No. I prepped this case myself.

602
00:23:22.488 --> 00:23:25.969
If we lose. and we won't.
there's no way we lose that big.

603
00:23:26.013 --> 00:23:27.536
I wish I were wrong.

604
00:23:27.580 --> 00:23:30.452
but our mirror juries
are exceptionally accurate.

605
00:23:30.496 --> 00:23:33.412
You can still minimize
your losses.

606
00:23:36.240 --> 00:23:38.460
Too late. This is the verdict.

607
00:23:38.504 --> 00:23:40.636
Let's see if you're
as good as you think you are.

608
00:23:40.680 --> 00:23:42.290
Yes. Craig.

609
00:23:47.382 --> 00:23:49.210
$47 million in damages.

610
00:23:49.253 --> 00:23:50.690
Right on the money.

611
00:23:50.733 --> 00:23:53.519
Aurora said our deal
is as good as done.

612
00:23:53.562 --> 00:23:56.173
She wants to come by TAC
later this week

613
00:23:56.217 --> 00:23:57.653
to see how the sausage is made.

614
00:23:58.785 --> 00:24:00.221
Well. congratulations.

615
00:24:00.264 --> 00:24:03.485
You just single-handedly
tripled TAC's business.

616
00:24:03.529 --> 00:24:07.010
The look on Bradley's face
was priceless.

617
00:24:07.054 --> 00:24:08.751
Well. we will celebrate
when this case is over.

618
00:24:08.795 --> 00:24:10.623
- all right? I got to go.
- Bye.

619
00:24:11.711 --> 00:24:13.190
- Hey there.
- How you doing?

620
00:24:13.234 --> 00:24:16.411
I'm Dr. Jason Bull.
This is Chester Palmer.Hey.

621
00:24:16.455 --> 00:24:18.195
Are you positive
that it's safe to be down here?

622
00:24:18.239 --> 00:24:20.284
I mean. the tenants have been
in a hotel for the last week.

623
00:24:20.328 --> 00:24:22.417
Uh. city does that out of
an abundance of caution.

624
00:24:22.461 --> 00:24:24.114
Yeah. But don't worry.

625
00:24:24.158 --> 00:24:25.420
This thing's been
shut down for a while.

626
00:24:25.464 --> 00:24:26.726
What are we looking at here?

627
00:24:26.769 --> 00:24:28.249
When it comes
to the boiler.

628
00:24:28.292 --> 00:24:29.685
pretty open-and-shut.

629
00:24:29.729 --> 00:24:31.208
Can see the exhaust pipe cracked

630
00:24:31.252 --> 00:24:32.514
in the area
that it was oxidized.

631
00:24:32.558 --> 00:24:34.342
Then it was mended
with furnace cement

632
00:24:34.385 --> 00:24:35.474
and duct tape.

633
00:24:35.517 --> 00:24:36.562
Is that
a reasonable repair?

634
00:24:36.605 --> 00:24:38.389
Yeah. sure. Happens
all the time.

635
00:24:38.433 --> 00:24:40.130
Your maintenance man
did a solid job.

636
00:24:40.174 --> 00:24:42.698
You know. much better than a lot
of the shoddy work I see.

637
00:24:42.742 --> 00:24:45.266
But there was
something strange.

638
00:24:45.309 --> 00:24:46.746
The second CO started leaking.

639
00:24:46.789 --> 00:24:50.140
this emergency damper here.
that should've shut off.

640
00:24:50.184 --> 00:24:52.229
triggered the whole system.
Shut it down.

641
00:24:52.273 --> 00:24:55.102
The first expert we talked to
said it didn't trigger

642
00:24:55.145 --> 00:24:56.799
because a wire was severed.

643
00:24:56.843 --> 00:24:58.758
He thought maybe rats
chewed through it?

644
00:24:58.801 --> 00:25:01.282
He's right about the wire.
but...

645
00:25:02.762 --> 00:25:04.241
Not rats.

646
00:25:04.285 --> 00:25:06.417
Rats never eat just one wire.

647
00:25:06.461 --> 00:25:07.984
They eat everything.

648
00:25:08.028 --> 00:25:09.725
And the rest
of the wiring's intact.

649
00:25:09.769 --> 00:25:12.336
Then how do you explain that?
To me.

650
00:25:12.380 --> 00:25:14.556
looks like somebody snipped it

651
00:25:14.600 --> 00:25:16.602
with wire cutters.

652
00:25:16.645 --> 00:25:19.561
Rob's been going after the
wrong guy this whole time.

653
00:25:19.605 --> 00:25:21.563
Ed wasn't negligent.

654
00:25:21.607 --> 00:25:23.522
Somebody murdered
those people.

655
00:25:30.137 --> 00:25:31.530
Sorry. Pass.

656
00:25:31.573 --> 00:25:32.922
What do you mean. pass?

657
00:25:32.966 --> 00:25:35.272
I'm not dropping the charges
against your client.

658
00:25:35.316 --> 00:25:37.231
Come on. Rob.

659
00:25:37.274 --> 00:25:39.189
Ed's boiler
was deliberately sabotaged.

660
00:25:39.233 --> 00:25:42.410
This is a sworn affidavit
by experts...That's

661
00:25:42.453 --> 00:25:44.455
one person's opinion.
We will find others
to back him up.

662
00:25:44.499 --> 00:25:45.631
I'm sure you will.

663
00:25:45.674 --> 00:25:47.546
But your original expert
doesn't agree.

664
00:25:47.589 --> 00:25:49.591
Otherwise. you would've come
to me with this weeks ago.

665
00:25:49.635 --> 00:25:50.810
But even if you're not convinced.

666
00:25:50.853 --> 00:25:52.246
you still have an obligation

667
00:25:52.289 --> 00:25:53.552
to investigate this further.

668
00:25:53.595 --> 00:25:55.118
This is a man's life. Rob.

669
00:25:55.162 --> 00:25:56.642
You don't have the monopoly
on giving a crap

670
00:25:56.685 --> 00:25:57.817
about other people. Chester.

671
00:25:57.860 --> 00:25:59.819
I just happen to disagree
with you

672
00:25:59.862 --> 00:26:02.386
on the facts.
How are you so stubborn?

673
00:26:03.474 --> 00:26:05.302
If there's nothing else
I can help you boys with...

674
00:26:05.346 --> 00:26:07.609
It's called confirmation bias.

675
00:26:07.653 --> 00:26:10.264
You made your case in the press
every chance you got.

676
00:26:10.307 --> 00:26:11.482
and now you can't admit
you're wrong

677
00:26:11.526 --> 00:26:13.310
without getting egg
all over your face.

678
00:26:13.354 --> 00:26:15.399
Do I use the media
to help sell my case?

679
00:26:15.443 --> 00:26:17.227
You bet your ass.
You want to know why?

680
00:26:17.271 --> 00:26:18.620
Weak case?

681
00:26:18.664 --> 00:26:20.579
Flexible ethics?

682
00:26:20.622 --> 00:26:22.929
Because in the courtroom.
you have a team of people

683
00:26:22.972 --> 00:26:25.758
whispering in your ear. digging
through jurors' digital lives.

684
00:26:25.801 --> 00:26:28.717
their trash.
psychoanalyzing every fart.

685
00:26:28.761 --> 00:26:32.068
Whoa. I don't think
we're that sophisticated.
Yeah. You both

686
00:26:32.112 --> 00:26:33.983
like to preach about ethics.
but TAC is turning

687
00:26:34.027 --> 00:26:35.898
the system I love
into an arms race.

688
00:26:35.942 --> 00:26:37.073
We're done here.

689
00:26:40.686 --> 00:26:42.122
We're throwing out
the old strategy.

690
00:26:43.166 --> 00:26:45.952
Now that we have shown our hand.

691
00:26:45.995 --> 00:26:47.693
Rob is gonna double down

692
00:26:47.736 --> 00:26:49.738
with his character assassination
of Ed.

693
00:26:49.782 --> 00:26:51.392
and we're gonna take advantage
of that.

694
00:26:51.435 --> 00:26:54.047
Instead of arguing that Ed is
a nice guy who made a mistake.

695
00:26:54.090 --> 00:26:55.657
I'll concede to the court

696
00:26:55.701 --> 00:26:57.572
that there were tenants
who disliked him.

697
00:26:57.616 --> 00:26:59.182
Hated him. even.

698
00:26:59.226 --> 00:27:01.489
And I'm gonna convince that jury
that one of those tenants

699
00:27:01.532 --> 00:27:04.100
- sabotaged that boiler to settle a score.
- That will resonate

700
00:27:04.144 --> 00:27:05.798
with the jurors
who have a Bad Actor Bias.

701
00:27:05.841 --> 00:27:07.843
but only if we have specifics.

702
00:27:07.887 --> 00:27:11.194
They'll want a bigger bad
to replace Ed.

703
00:27:11.238 --> 00:27:13.762
Danny.
any of the tenants have a gripe

704
00:27:13.806 --> 00:27:16.547
that could've motivated
the sabotage of the boiler?

705
00:27:16.591 --> 00:27:18.898
Yeah. maybe this woman.
Kristi Walker.

706
00:27:18.941 --> 00:27:20.203
A few tenants

707
00:27:20.247 --> 00:27:23.076
remembered her having
a screaming match with Ed

708
00:27:23.119 --> 00:27:24.730
shortly before the leak.
Plus. she wasn't there

709
00:27:24.773 --> 00:27:25.861
the night it happened.
and she hasn't

710
00:27:25.905 --> 00:27:27.036
returned any of my calls.

711
00:27:27.080 --> 00:27:28.647
Kristi has a record
for possession.

712
00:27:28.690 --> 00:27:30.257
She's also the only tenant

713
00:27:30.300 --> 00:27:32.172
that hasn't checked into the
free hotel provided by the city.

714
00:27:32.215 --> 00:27:34.827
Maybe she's making herself
scarce for a reason.

715
00:27:34.870 --> 00:27:37.699
Okay. You two

716
00:27:37.743 --> 00:27:39.048
find Kristi.

717
00:27:39.092 --> 00:27:40.876
If she did it.
maybe we can get her to trip up

718
00:27:40.920 --> 00:27:42.530
and confess.

719
00:27:42.573 --> 00:27:44.010
I have no family.

720
00:27:44.053 --> 00:27:47.187
so I put all my time and energy
into my building.

721
00:27:47.230 --> 00:27:49.232
Maybe it sounds corny.

722
00:27:49.276 --> 00:27:52.583
but I think of my tenants
as family.

723
00:27:52.627 --> 00:27:56.239
The fact that this
happened under my roof...

724
00:27:58.241 --> 00:27:59.808
I'm devastated.

725
00:27:59.852 --> 00:28:02.724
They're surprised
by how much they like him.

726
00:28:02.768 --> 00:28:05.509
- Things are looking up on our end.
- Ed. I want to talk to you

727
00:28:05.553 --> 00:28:07.468
about one tenant in particular:

728
00:28:07.511 --> 00:28:09.862
Kristi Walker.

729
00:28:09.905 --> 00:28:12.865
Now. shortly before the leak.
the two of you had an argument.

730
00:28:12.908 --> 00:28:15.171
Do you recall
what that argument was about?

731
00:28:15.215 --> 00:28:18.218
Sure. Uh.
she was behind on her rent.

732
00:28:18.261 --> 00:28:20.176
and I told her
I was gonna have to start

733
00:28:20.220 --> 00:28:22.004
the process of evicting her.

734
00:28:22.048 --> 00:28:24.615
And how did she take that?
Not well.

735
00:28:24.659 --> 00:28:28.010
She screamed at me
that she had nowhere else to go.

736
00:28:28.054 --> 00:28:30.883
I felt bad.
but I'd already let it slide

737
00:28:30.926 --> 00:28:33.276
for months
beyond what I was required to

738
00:28:33.320 --> 00:28:34.974
by the rent forbearance.

739
00:28:35.017 --> 00:28:37.193
She sounds
like a desperate woman.

740
00:28:37.237 --> 00:28:39.587
You think that that's
a fair characterization

741
00:28:39.630 --> 00:28:41.589
from your experience with her?

742
00:28:41.632 --> 00:28:43.983
It's not nice to say. but yeah.

743
00:28:44.026 --> 00:28:46.072
She had a lot of problems.

744
00:28:46.115 --> 00:28:48.683
Drugs. trouble with the cops.

745
00:28:48.727 --> 00:28:50.293
Hypothetically. if...

746
00:28:50.337 --> 00:28:52.078
if a tenant like Kristi Walker

747
00:28:52.121 --> 00:28:55.342
wanted to stop
the eviction process

748
00:28:55.385 --> 00:28:56.909
while continuing to live
in your building

749
00:28:56.952 --> 00:28:58.345
without paying rent.

750
00:28:58.388 --> 00:29:00.869
is there a situation
that would make that possible?

751
00:29:00.913 --> 00:29:02.915
Yes. In New York City.

752
00:29:02.958 --> 00:29:05.613
there's a law that allows
tenants to withhold rent

753
00:29:05.656 --> 00:29:07.789
if they don't have
adequate heat.

754
00:29:07.833 --> 00:29:10.139
And what provides heat
for your building?

755
00:29:10.183 --> 00:29:11.750
The boiler.

756
00:29:11.793 --> 00:29:14.274
The same boiler
that experts testified

757
00:29:14.317 --> 00:29:16.232
had been
intentionally sabotaged?

758
00:29:16.276 --> 00:29:17.277
That's correct.

759
00:29:17.320 --> 00:29:18.931
So. anyone

760
00:29:18.974 --> 00:29:21.107
could gain access
to that boiler room

761
00:29:21.150 --> 00:29:22.804
and cut that wire?

762
00:29:22.848 --> 00:29:25.111
The door to the boiler room
wasn't kept locked.

763
00:29:25.154 --> 00:29:28.636
Anybody could have gotten
inside there if they wanted to.

764
00:29:28.679 --> 00:29:30.029
Including Kristi Walker.

765
00:29:30.072 --> 00:29:31.900
a desperate.
drug-addicted woman...

766
00:29:31.944 --> 00:29:33.902
Objection! Inflammatory....
who was about to be evicted

767
00:29:33.946 --> 00:29:35.817
with nowhere else to go?

768
00:29:35.861 --> 00:29:37.384
And that
is definitely speculation.

769
00:29:37.427 --> 00:29:38.907
Sustained.
You are well out of bounds.

770
00:29:38.951 --> 00:29:40.169
Mr. Palmer. and you know it.

771
00:29:40.213 --> 00:29:43.172
My apologies. Your Honor.
I withdraw.

772
00:29:43.216 --> 00:29:45.218
No further questions.

773
00:29:48.177 --> 00:29:49.657
Okay. that went well.

774
00:29:49.700 --> 00:29:52.007
Any update on finding Kristi
to bring this home?

775
00:29:52.051 --> 00:29:53.313
I just got her phone's
last known location.

776
00:29:53.356 --> 00:29:55.968
Danny's on her way now.
With a board this green.

777
00:29:56.011 --> 00:29:57.447
we might not even need her.

778
00:29:57.491 --> 00:29:58.971
Never hurts to put a cherry
on the sundae.

779
00:30:02.975 --> 00:30:05.151
Aurora Clifton
is on her way up.

780
00:30:05.194 --> 00:30:06.848
Excuse me.

781
00:30:09.068 --> 00:30:11.722
Aurora. welcome to TAC.
Let's start the tour

782
00:30:11.766 --> 00:30:13.724
in our state-of-the-art
mock courtroom.

783
00:30:13.768 --> 00:30:15.857
Actually. uh.
I'm gonna stop you.

784
00:30:15.901 --> 00:30:18.033
There's no need for the tour.
Why not?

785
00:30:18.077 --> 00:30:20.166
You put a lot of effort
into pitching me.

786
00:30:20.209 --> 00:30:22.995
so I thought I owed it to you
to tell you in person.

787
00:30:23.038 --> 00:30:24.866
I'm hiring Bradley Lena

788
00:30:24.910 --> 00:30:26.868
to handle
our trial science needs.

789
00:30:26.912 --> 00:30:28.870
I'm sorry. I don't understand.

790
00:30:28.914 --> 00:30:31.786
Bradley told me that
you left TAC to join his firm

791
00:30:31.830 --> 00:30:33.353
and then abruptly went back
to TAC.

792
00:30:33.396 --> 00:30:35.703
I can't trust some
of the most important part

793
00:30:35.746 --> 00:30:37.183
of my business
to someone who's flaky.

794
00:30:37.226 --> 00:30:40.099
Flaky? I didn't leave Bradley
because I'm flaky.

795
00:30:40.142 --> 00:30:42.362
I left because
I didn't want to partner

796
00:30:42.405 --> 00:30:44.233
with someone
as unethical as he is.

797
00:30:44.277 --> 00:30:48.107
Case in point. that man
stole his algorithm from me.

798
00:30:48.150 --> 00:30:49.891
So? That's good business.

799
00:30:49.935 --> 00:30:51.893
Question is
why you'd let someone

800
00:30:51.937 --> 00:30:53.373
steal your most valuable asset.

801
00:30:53.416 --> 00:30:56.419
Aurora. let's sit down. talk
this through. You will see

802
00:30:56.463 --> 00:30:58.160
that partnering with TAC
is better business.

803
00:30:58.204 --> 00:31:01.207
Marissa. you're a smart woman.
but you let yourself get played.

804
00:31:01.250 --> 00:31:03.209
I can't have weakness
on my team.

805
00:31:03.252 --> 00:31:05.994
I need killers. and Bradley's a killer.

806
00:31:10.956 --> 00:31:12.000
Good luck.

807
00:31:27.276 --> 00:31:29.104
Excuse me. Kristi?

808
00:31:29.148 --> 00:31:30.758
Who the hell are you?

809
00:31:30.801 --> 00:31:32.891
Sorry to startle you.
I'm an investigator

810
00:31:32.934 --> 00:31:34.936
looking into
the carbon monoxide incident

811
00:31:34.980 --> 00:31:36.285
at your apartment building.
Leave me alone.

812
00:31:36.329 --> 00:31:38.461
I just want to talk.
I said get lost.

813
00:31:38.505 --> 00:31:40.507
Or I could tell the
security guard over there

814
00:31:40.550 --> 00:31:41.987
to check your pockets.

815
00:31:43.423 --> 00:31:45.338
Just have a few questions.

816
00:31:45.381 --> 00:31:48.080
Help me out. and I'll pay for
whatever's in your jacket. Deal?

817
00:31:49.124 --> 00:31:50.212
What do you want?

818
00:31:50.256 --> 00:31:51.257
I think you know
what really happened

819
00:31:51.300 --> 00:31:52.780
in your apartment building.

820
00:31:52.823 --> 00:31:54.216
I don't want to get involved.

821
00:31:54.260 --> 00:31:55.783
I'm sure you didn't mean

822
00:31:55.826 --> 00:31:56.958
to hurt anyone.

823
00:31:57.002 --> 00:31:58.960
What are you talking about?

824
00:31:59.004 --> 00:32:00.788
You broke the boiler.
didn't you?

825
00:32:00.831 --> 00:32:02.790
What? No. I didn't...
I didn't break that boiler.

826
00:32:02.833 --> 00:32:04.009
Come on. You got
in a fight with Ed.

827
00:32:04.052 --> 00:32:05.401
You tried to get out
of paying your rent.

828
00:32:05.445 --> 00:32:06.794
Things didn't go
the way you thought they would.

829
00:32:06.837 --> 00:32:09.101
No. I-I yelled at Ed.
but then Nicholas.

830
00:32:09.144 --> 00:32:11.233
he warned me not to get
on Ed's bad side.

831
00:32:11.277 --> 00:32:14.236
and so I dropped it.
I-I didn't break that boiler.

832
00:32:14.280 --> 00:32:15.803
Wait. wait. wait.
The maintenance guy

833
00:32:15.846 --> 00:32:17.196
told you not to get
on Ed's bad side?

834
00:32:17.239 --> 00:32:18.501
Why?

835
00:32:19.589 --> 00:32:22.462
Because he said he knew things
about Ed. Scary things.

836
00:32:22.505 --> 00:32:24.159
That's how he got his job
and a place to live.

837
00:32:24.203 --> 00:32:26.466
by blackmailing him.
And then Nicholas warned me.

838
00:32:26.509 --> 00:32:28.337
and now he's dead.
So. you think

839
00:32:28.381 --> 00:32:30.383
Ed leaked poison
in his own building

840
00:32:30.426 --> 00:32:32.820
just to silence Nicholas?

841
00:32:32.863 --> 00:32:34.169
Yeah.
Now you can arrest him. right?

842
00:32:34.213 --> 00:32:35.518
Aren't you a cop?

843
00:32:35.562 --> 00:32:37.172
I said I was an investigator.

844
00:32:38.217 --> 00:32:39.958
Wait. who do you work for?

845
00:32:40.001 --> 00:32:41.829
Oh. my God.

846
00:32:41.872 --> 00:32:44.179
You work for Ed.
Kristi. wait.

847
00:32:44.223 --> 00:32:45.311
Hey. hey!

848
00:32:45.354 --> 00:32:47.313
Kristi. wait!
Hey. empty your pockets!

849
00:32:47.356 --> 00:32:48.488
Damn it.

850
00:32:54.015 --> 00:32:55.974
Let me get this straight.
Ed isn't guilty

851
00:32:56.017 --> 00:32:57.149
of negligent homicide.

852
00:32:57.192 --> 00:32:59.978
He's guilty of mass murder?

853
00:33:01.066 --> 00:33:02.937
I'm just telling you
what Kristi said.

854
00:33:02.981 --> 00:33:05.809
Even if Nicholas had dirt on Ed
and Ed wanted him dead.

855
00:33:05.853 --> 00:33:07.986
a carbon monoxide leak

856
00:33:08.029 --> 00:33:10.205
doesn't sound
like the smartest plan to me.

857
00:33:10.249 --> 00:33:13.426
Nicholas's apartment was
directly above the boiler room.

858
00:33:13.469 --> 00:33:15.819
If anyone was gonna die.
it was gonna be him.

859
00:33:15.863 --> 00:33:17.430
Well. sure.
but five innocent people

860
00:33:17.473 --> 00:33:18.822
were killed in the process.

861
00:33:18.866 --> 00:33:21.912
If Ed's okay with that.
he's a monster.

862
00:33:21.956 --> 00:33:23.827
Kristi Walker has a long history
of drug abuse

863
00:33:23.871 --> 00:33:27.135
and every reason in the world
to want to deflect blame.

864
00:33:27.179 --> 00:33:30.356
True. but I saw real fear
in her face.

865
00:33:30.399 --> 00:33:32.314
Fear of going to prison.
Danny.

866
00:33:32.358 --> 00:33:33.489
Maybe.

867
00:33:33.533 --> 00:33:35.317
Well. Bull.
did you get any sense

868
00:33:35.361 --> 00:33:38.016
that Ed is capable
of something like that?

869
00:33:38.059 --> 00:33:39.843
No. Not at all.

870
00:33:39.887 --> 00:33:41.845
I mean. guy's a nervous wreck

871
00:33:41.889 --> 00:33:44.979
and seems to be showing
genuine empathy for the victims.

872
00:33:45.023 --> 00:33:47.503
I just don't see a sociopath.
I'm sorry.

873
00:33:47.547 --> 00:33:50.115
So. what do we do
about Kristi's story?

874
00:33:50.158 --> 00:33:53.161
Nothing.
Our job is to defend Ed.

875
00:33:53.205 --> 00:33:56.425
Digging any further
risks damaging him.

876
00:33:56.469 --> 00:33:59.037
So we rest our case.

877
00:33:59.080 --> 00:34:00.864
And don't tell
Chunk about this.

878
00:34:00.908 --> 00:34:02.866
He's got to sell that
closing argument tomorrow.

879
00:34:02.910 --> 00:34:06.174
and I don't want him
having any doubts about Ed.

880
00:34:06.218 --> 00:34:08.046
Multiple experts

881
00:34:08.089 --> 00:34:11.440
confirmed that someone
cut that wire.

882
00:34:11.484 --> 00:34:15.227
Someone deliberately sabotaged
the boiler in Ed's building.

883
00:34:15.270 --> 00:34:18.882
That wasn't negligence.
That was a deliberate act.

884
00:34:18.926 --> 00:34:20.928
And yet the prosecution chooses

885
00:34:20.971 --> 00:34:23.322
to ignore this fact
and persecute

886
00:34:23.365 --> 00:34:24.975
an innocent man.

887
00:34:25.976 --> 00:34:28.588
Ed Wilson is a kind.

888
00:34:28.631 --> 00:34:32.896
responsible.
hardworking man.

889
00:34:32.940 --> 00:34:36.248
Ed already lost so much.

890
00:34:36.291 --> 00:34:39.468
You must not allow
the prosecution

891
00:34:39.512 --> 00:34:42.602
to take away anything more
from this man.

892
00:34:42.645 --> 00:34:46.258
You must find him innocent.

893
00:34:50.262 --> 00:34:51.611
Dr. Bull.

894
00:34:53.395 --> 00:34:56.398
Thanks so much
for everything.

895
00:34:56.442 --> 00:34:58.444
If the jury breaks my way.
I know you're the guy

896
00:34:58.487 --> 00:35:00.098
who kept me out of prison.

897
00:35:05.059 --> 00:35:06.408
Of course. You're welcome.

898
00:35:07.975 --> 00:35:10.282
Do you mind
if I ask you a question?

899
00:35:10.325 --> 00:35:14.677
Um. you said
that you owed Nicholas a favor.

900
00:35:14.721 --> 00:35:16.984
What do you mean?

901
00:35:17.027 --> 00:35:18.942
The other day. you said...
how'd you put it?...

902
00:35:18.986 --> 00:35:20.944
that you owed Nicholas a solid.

903
00:35:20.988 --> 00:35:22.511
And. if you don't mind.

904
00:35:22.555 --> 00:35:24.948
I was just wondering.
what was that?

905
00:35:24.992 --> 00:35:26.994
Oh. Uh...

906
00:35:27.037 --> 00:35:29.953
Well. back when I was working
job-to-job as a contractor.

907
00:35:29.997 --> 00:35:34.088
Nicholas hooked me up with a big
kitchen renovation project.

908
00:35:34.132 --> 00:35:35.481
Why?

909
00:35:35.524 --> 00:35:37.004
Does this have anything

910
00:35:37.047 --> 00:35:39.006
to do with my case?
No.

911
00:35:39.049 --> 00:35:41.574
I'm just a curious man.

912
00:35:46.056 --> 00:35:47.971
There's a lot to do fast.

913
00:35:48.015 --> 00:35:49.625
You'll have to come to Chicago
and meet

914
00:35:49.669 --> 00:35:51.627
Cooper Ellis. get up to speed
on our current caseload.

915
00:35:51.671 --> 00:35:54.369
I will get on a plane tonight
if you want.

916
00:35:55.588 --> 00:35:57.155
A bottle
of Château Réserve de Loire

917
00:35:57.198 --> 00:35:59.505
compliments of the lady
at the bar.

918
00:36:02.334 --> 00:36:04.292
Oh.

919
00:36:04.336 --> 00:36:05.902
Let me.

920
00:36:05.946 --> 00:36:08.383
Marissa. how kind of you.

921
00:36:08.427 --> 00:36:11.995
I didn't want you to think that
there were any hard feelings.

922
00:36:12.039 --> 00:36:14.563
All's fair in love
and war. right?

923
00:36:14.607 --> 00:36:16.086
Right.

924
00:36:17.262 --> 00:36:19.002
Congratulations. by the way.

925
00:36:19.046 --> 00:36:21.091
You stole my algorithm.

926
00:36:21.135 --> 00:36:22.658
my job.

927
00:36:22.702 --> 00:36:25.357
But I won the real prize.

928
00:36:25.400 --> 00:36:27.359
What's that supposed to mean?

929
00:36:27.402 --> 00:36:29.578
I met with Matthew Price.

930
00:36:29.622 --> 00:36:32.320
the general counsel
for Wellman Hospitality.

931
00:36:32.364 --> 00:36:36.019
Showed him my mock trial results
for the wrongful death case.

932
00:36:36.063 --> 00:36:39.371
He was so angry that they paid
double what they would have

933
00:36:39.414 --> 00:36:41.460
if they'd settled. he
decided right then and there

934
00:36:41.503 --> 00:36:45.681
to fire Ellis & Clifton
and hire TAC instead.

935
00:36:45.725 --> 00:36:47.248
Oh. look.

936
00:36:47.292 --> 00:36:49.250
Aurora must be getting the news
right now.

937
00:36:49.294 --> 00:36:51.121
That's fun.

938
00:36:53.298 --> 00:36:55.256
That's her biggest client.I know.

939
00:36:55.300 --> 00:36:57.258
Enjoy your new partnership.

940
00:36:57.302 --> 00:37:00.130
Could I get another bottle
of champagne. please? To go?

941
00:37:00.174 --> 00:37:02.350
The good stuff this time.

942
00:37:03.438 --> 00:37:05.135
Erik. I'm worried. too.

943
00:37:05.179 --> 00:37:07.660
I'm the one
who's here dealing with it.

944
00:37:07.703 --> 00:37:10.402
That's not what I meant.
Look. the doctor said

945
00:37:10.445 --> 00:37:12.055
if we want to help Mauricio
without meds.

946
00:37:12.099 --> 00:37:14.362
it's gonna take
a lot more time and focus.

947
00:37:14.406 --> 00:37:16.364
Tutors. making sure
he's getting exercise

948
00:37:16.408 --> 00:37:18.714
before school in the morning.

949
00:37:18.758 --> 00:37:21.543
Maybe I can cut back
on my hours at work.

950
00:37:21.587 --> 00:37:23.328
I don't know.

951
00:37:24.546 --> 00:37:26.548
For the woman of the hour.
Thanks.

952
00:37:26.592 --> 00:37:28.376
Hope you're ready for
a boatload of work.

953
00:37:28.420 --> 00:37:29.464
Bring it on.

954
00:37:30.509 --> 00:37:32.162
Oh. Taylor.
we're celebrating.

955
00:37:32.206 --> 00:37:34.164
Have a glass of bubbly.

956
00:37:34.208 --> 00:37:36.297
Um. by the way.
I'm gonna need you

957
00:37:36.341 --> 00:37:38.734
to start vetting
some new cyber analysts.

958
00:37:38.778 --> 00:37:41.389
Bull and I want you
to manage a team.

959
00:37:41.433 --> 00:37:43.783
- Manage a team?
- It's a lot more responsibility.

960
00:37:43.826 --> 00:37:45.263
but I promise you. it comes

961
00:37:45.306 --> 00:37:47.395
- with a bigger paycheck. too.
- Ka-ching.

962
00:37:50.311 --> 00:37:52.574
Because he said he knew things
about Ed. Scary things.

963
00:37:52.618 --> 00:37:53.793
That's how he got his job

964
00:37:53.836 --> 00:37:55.534
and a place to live.
by blackmailing him.

965
00:37:55.577 --> 00:37:57.840
And then Nicholas warned me.
and now he's dead.

966
00:37:57.884 --> 00:37:59.494
Hey. boss.

967
00:37:59.538 --> 00:38:01.191
Little champagne?

968
00:38:01.235 --> 00:38:03.281
Uh...

969
00:38:03.324 --> 00:38:05.805
No. I'm not really
in a champagne mood.

970
00:38:06.849 --> 00:38:09.156
What's wrong?
You worried about the verdict?

971
00:38:10.157 --> 00:38:12.115
Yeah. in a way.

972
00:38:12.159 --> 00:38:15.293
Something
just doesn't feel right.

973
00:38:16.381 --> 00:38:17.643
Dr. Bull?

974
00:38:19.427 --> 00:38:21.516
Hey. Ed. What're you doing here?

975
00:38:21.560 --> 00:38:22.778
Sorry for just
dropping by like this.

976
00:38:22.822 --> 00:38:25.738
but. uh. can we
talk for a minute?

977
00:38:25.781 --> 00:38:27.261
In private?

978
00:38:28.480 --> 00:38:29.829
Uh. sure.

979
00:38:35.400 --> 00:38:37.184
What can I do for you. Ed?

980
00:38:38.228 --> 00:38:41.406
Did I ever tell you how I got
my first break in real estate?

981
00:38:43.190 --> 00:38:44.322
Ten years ago.

982
00:38:44.365 --> 00:38:46.802
when I was still a contractor.

983
00:38:46.846 --> 00:38:50.197
I was renovating a three-unit
brownstone in Greenpoint.

984
00:38:50.240 --> 00:38:54.288
I convinced the owner
to sell it to me off-market.

985
00:38:54.332 --> 00:38:56.159
Wasn't easy
to get the money together.

986
00:38:56.203 --> 00:38:59.511
but it was gonna be mine.

987
00:38:59.554 --> 00:39:01.730
Then. last minute.

988
00:39:01.774 --> 00:39:03.689
friends of the owners

989
00:39:03.732 --> 00:39:06.561
decided to buy the place
for their daughter

990
00:39:06.605 --> 00:39:10.260
as an investment property.
and they outbid me.

991
00:39:11.305 --> 00:39:12.872
Yeah.

992
00:39:12.915 --> 00:39:15.178
Real estate's
tricky. Listen.

993
00:39:15.222 --> 00:39:16.528
Ed. can we do this another time?

994
00:39:16.571 --> 00:39:19.182
I worked on my hands and knees
for months fixing up

995
00:39:19.226 --> 00:39:21.533
that place.
I knew every inch of it.

996
00:39:21.576 --> 00:39:24.362
Every board. every screw.

997
00:39:24.405 --> 00:39:27.408
And they were just gonna give it
to that spoiled brat?

998
00:39:27.452 --> 00:39:29.671
I couldn't let that happen.

999
00:39:29.715 --> 00:39:30.933
You know me.

1000
00:39:30.977 --> 00:39:33.414
I'm a problem-solver.

1001
00:39:34.459 --> 00:39:36.374
So. one night.

1002
00:39:36.417 --> 00:39:38.680
I followed the daughter.

1003
00:39:39.725 --> 00:39:42.684
Jodie Comroe was her name.

1004
00:39:42.728 --> 00:39:44.338
I'd put a nail in her tire.

1005
00:39:44.382 --> 00:39:47.602
and when it went flat.
I came to her rescue.

1006
00:39:49.604 --> 00:39:50.736
Stupid little girl

1007
00:39:50.779 --> 00:39:53.260
didn't even know
how to change a tire.

1008
00:39:55.262 --> 00:39:57.656
Anyway. instead of changing it.

1009
00:39:57.699 --> 00:40:00.310
I bashed her head in
with the tire iron.

1010
00:40:00.354 --> 00:40:02.661
I put her body in a barrel

1011
00:40:02.704 --> 00:40:04.880
and buried it
in Saunders Woods

1012
00:40:04.924 --> 00:40:06.708
out in Pennsylvania.

1013
00:40:06.752 --> 00:40:09.276
Nice. quiet spot

1014
00:40:09.319 --> 00:40:12.671
near some old columns
above the creek.

1015
00:40:12.714 --> 00:40:15.500
That's what Nicholas had on you.

1016
00:40:15.543 --> 00:40:17.719
He knew about the murder.

1017
00:40:19.765 --> 00:40:21.244
The cops questioned me.

1018
00:40:21.288 --> 00:40:23.812
but Nicholas gave me an alibi.
and they moved on.

1019
00:40:23.856 --> 00:40:25.858
It was all ancient history

1020
00:40:25.901 --> 00:40:29.383
until he showed up
demanding a job

1021
00:40:29.427 --> 00:40:30.950
and a place to stay.

1022
00:40:30.993 --> 00:40:33.735
and then he started asking
for more and more cash.

1023
00:40:34.997 --> 00:40:36.651
If only he wasn't so greedy.

1024
00:40:36.695 --> 00:40:39.611
none of this
would've had to happen.

1025
00:40:39.654 --> 00:40:42.614
Your tenants. Ed.

1026
00:40:42.657 --> 00:40:45.486
You didn't even care
how many you killed.

1027
00:40:46.574 --> 00:40:49.316
I couldn't take the risk
of him talking.

1028
00:40:50.535 --> 00:40:52.362
I knew I'd get sued
for the leak.

1029
00:40:52.406 --> 00:40:54.626
but that's
what insurance is for.

1030
00:40:55.975 --> 00:40:59.631
The one thing I didn't count on
was getting arrested.

1031
00:41:02.329 --> 00:41:04.505
But then you came to my rescue.

1032
00:41:07.639 --> 00:41:10.076
Why are you telling me this now?

1033
00:41:11.556 --> 00:41:13.819
When you asked me
about Nicholas...

1034
00:41:15.342 --> 00:41:16.648
...I could tell.

1035
00:41:16.691 --> 00:41:18.650
You knew something.

1036
00:41:18.693 --> 00:41:21.522
You may not have known
everything yet.

1037
00:41:21.566 --> 00:41:24.351
but I think
you would've kept digging.

1038
00:41:25.352 --> 00:41:26.832
You're the type
who'd need to know

1039
00:41:26.875 --> 00:41:29.095
if you were wrong about me.

1040
00:41:30.357 --> 00:41:32.446
And if you figured out enough
on your own.

1041
00:41:32.490 --> 00:41:34.492
you could bring it
to the police.

1042
00:41:37.016 --> 00:41:39.453
But since I'm telling you
myself...

1043
00:41:42.456 --> 00:41:44.719
It's privileged.

1044
00:41:44.763 --> 00:41:47.069
That's right.

1045
00:41:47.113 --> 00:41:50.029
Now it's our little secret.

